			<title>Oculus Rift</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?77311-Oculus-Rift&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Fri, 10 Oct 2014 20:50:27 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[Just in case anyone wants to get a decent idea of how the Oculus Rift looks and whether you should buy it, I present you with this: 
 
http://vr.mkeblx.net/oculus-sim/ 
 
Check the "Low Persistence" box, and select different resolutions, while holding your face ~3" away. 
 
You'll basically see...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>Just in case anyone wants to get a decent idea of how the Oculus Rift looks and whether you should buy it, I present you with this:<br />
<br />
<a href="http://vr.mkeblx.net/oculus-sim/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://vr.mkeblx.net/oculus-sim/</a><br />
<br />
Check the &quot;Low Persistence&quot; box, and select different resolutions, while holding your face ~3&quot; away.<br />
<br />
You'll basically see something like this: <a href="http://i.ytimg.com/vi/pllSQFKF1k8/maxresdefault.jpg" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://i.ytimg.com/vi/pllSQFKF1k8/maxresdefault.jpg</a><br />
<br />
The Dev Kit 2 is 1080p, and the Crescent Bay Prototype they've been playing with is the 1440p version labeled CV1, and I haven't played with that one, but I hear the screen door problem is gone, the only problem is that you can see the color shift from the subpixels (meaning instead of seeing white, you see a 'rainbow' effect of red, blue, green. <br />
<br />
Playing around with the slider, you can kind of see how the CV1 prototype looks pretty good, but still has some problems.  But the other issue the CV1 fixes that I haven't been able to play with is the refresh rate.<br />
<br />
Tearing on your monitor is a little awful, but tearing on the Rift can make you sick incredibly fast.  Oculus says they're aiming for a minimum of a 90hz refresh.  DK2 has a 75hz refresh, and on simulator style games that seems adequate. I didn't get sick playing Euro Truck Simulator.  But on action games?  I played Windlands for ~30-45 minutes.  When I finished, I thought the nasty cold/sinus infection I'd been fighting for a week had come back, as I was sweating, and felt nauseous. After a few minutes for having the Rift off of my face, I realized for the second time in my life, I had become motion sick.  To be sort of fair to everyone involved, I was doing stupid things.  I was &quot;swinging&quot; on a tree at high enough velocities that I launching myself up into the air several hundred feet to grab other trees.  They have some different options for targeting your grappling hooks, which may be required for anyone playing it for extended periods.<br />
<br />
Playing Euro Truck Simulator with the Rift on was fun. I don't think I would ever play that game without a Rift, but playing with the Rift was pretty awesome. being able to look at an angle to view your mirror and still see the road in front of you is a lot more natural than using key bindings or mouse look to angle a different way.<br />
<br />
Also, I have awful vision (about -9x in both eyes) and wear contacts. I was worried I wouldn't be able to use a Rift with it so close to my face, or if I did that I might have to remove my contacts, but I ultimately didn't have a problem with that.  It worked fine without removing my contacts, or making adjustments from my friend who was using his glasses.</div>

]]></content:encoded>
